---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import TeslaChain from '@/components/react/TeslaChain.tsx';
import Formula from '@/components/ui/Formula.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="TESLA key chain"
  description="How the OSNMA TESLA one-way key chain is generated, disclosed and verified."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="4 · Cryptographic machinery"
    title="The TESLA key chain"
    lead="A pre-computed chain of keys, released one at a time in reverse, turns a cheap symmetric MAC into proof that only Galileo could have produced the data."
  />

  <p>
    A TESLA chain is built backward from a secret. The provider picks a random
    seed <Formula tex="K_N" />, then derives each earlier key from the next with a
    one-way function <Formula tex="F" />, all the way down to the root
    <Formula tex="K_0" /> <DocRef doc="icd" section="6.4" />:
  </p>
  <Formula tex="K_i = F(K_{i+1}) = \operatorname{trunc}\big(l_k,\ \operatorname{hash}(K_{i+1}\ \|\ GST_{SF,i}\ \|\ \alpha)\big)" display />
  <p>
    Because <Formula tex="F" /> is one-way, anyone can hash a disclosed key
    <em>backward</em> toward the root, but nobody can run it <em>forward</em> to
    predict the next, still-secret key. That asymmetry is the whole trick.
  </p>

  <h2>Generation, broadcast, verification</h2>
  <p>
    Keys are generated seed-to-root but <strong>broadcast root-first</strong>: the
    root <Formula tex="K_0" /> is published and authenticated up front (in the
    signed DSM-KROOT), then one key is disclosed per 30-second subframe. Walk a
    received key back to the root below:
  </p>

  <TeslaChain client:visible />

  <h2>Why delay equals authentication</h2>
  <p>
    Each tag in a subframe is a MAC computed with a key that is still secret at
    that moment. The matching key is disclosed in a <em>later</em> subframe
    <DocRef doc="rxg" section="5.5.4" />. A receiver buffers the data and its tag,
    waits for the key, confirms the key belongs to the chain, then recomputes the
    MAC. A forger, not knowing the key in advance, cannot fabricate a tag that will
    later check out.
  </p>

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      One chain serves the whole constellation. Every OSNMA satellite discloses the
      same key at the same epoch, which is what lets one satellite's tags
      authenticate another satellite's data — <em>cross-authentication</em>.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="security">
    <p>
      The delay only protects you if the key really was secret when the tag
      arrived. That is enforced by the loose time check on the
      <a href="/receiver/time-sync">time synchronisation gate</a> page.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="level-engineer">
    <h3>The chain pattern α</h3>
    <p>
      The 48-bit pattern <Formula tex="\alpha" /> from the DSM-KROOT is mixed into
      every derivation, and <Formula tex="GST_{SF}" /> binds each key to a specific
      subframe in time. Together they make the chain unique and prevent a key from
      a different time or chain being substituted.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
